Tuan,<br>
<br>
There is an even deeper issue involved once we begin to add in the so-called properties of the Christian God. Let's consider the idea of omniscience (God is all knowing). If God is all knowing then he surely knows what he will do with regard to the future of the world. <br>
<br>
For illustration purposes: Cendan preaches salvation through baptism to little Sally who says no because she is a good Western Conference Baptist who believes the blood of Christ saves her through faith alone. She gets crushed by a Mack Truck seconds later and finds her self before the throne of God. What is going to happen? Cendan says she will fry, her baptist minister told her that she would go to heaven.<br>
<br>
Now if God is omniscient, then he already know that little Sally had followed what she knew about Jesus and trusted individuals along the journey to teach her truth. Infact, it is the model Christ used with the apostles and the church. God knew, before the creation of the world, if he is omnipotent, that he would have to send Sally to hell (if what Cendan is saying is true). Eventhoough, little Sally did all she could with what knowledge she had. She did her best.<br>
<br>
If God is omniscient then why would he allow such disparate views of his salvation plan to exist? Isn't God decieving us if he does nothing at all to clarify his salvation plan? In fact, isn't it evil to knowingly create a world in which some of the denizens will live in eternal torment? Cendan, you think most of us are going to hell, that the path is narrow to heaven.<br>
<br>
As an aside, I will call a truce to flaming you Cendan. I am very interested in these issues and I would welcome your input. I only ask you do the same.  <p>Lurikeen Mali'Kyre<BR>
